mericanized form of North German <b>Fullmann</b>: variant of <b>Vollmann</b> (see   Vollman  ).","English: possibly a Middle English nickname from <i>foul</i>, <i>ful</i> ‘foul, dirty’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."],"variants":[{"name":"Vollman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Inge.","Americanized form of German <b>Vollmann</b>: variant of   Volkmann  ."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably a respelling of   Laura  , that coincides in form with the German spelling of the same name and also with the medieval English given name."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Nycolas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]},{"name":"Nicolao","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Nycolas Fullman was born about 1483, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. He married Lady of Kent England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 10 October 1563, in Blendon, London, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 81, and was buried in Blendon, London, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1483–10 October 1563":"umbes 1483–10. oktoober 1563","1483–1563":"1483–1563","1502–1550":"1502–1550","1499–1550":"1499–1550","Abt 1483":"umbes 1483","1502":"1502","1499":"1499","10 October 1563":"10. oktoober 1563","1563":"1563","1550":"1550","1483":"1483","London, City of London, Greater London, England, United Kingdom":"Blendon, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Long Row, Norfolk, England ":"Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1483–10 October 1563":"noin 1483–10. lokakuuta 1563","1483–1563":"1483–1563","1502–1550":"1502–1550","1499–1550":"1499–1550","Abt 1483":"noin 1483","1502":"1502","1499":"1499","10 October 1563":"10. lokakuuta 1563","1563":"1563","1550":"1550","1483":"1483","London, City of London, Greater London, England, United Kingdom":"Blendon, London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England",", , Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","En